# Advanced World History O/X
> Key turning points in world history
@languageCode: en
// Swiq — https://swiq.jiun.dev/set/seed.en.history.world-advanced/

The French Revolution began in 1789, marked by the storming of the Bastille. | O | The storming of the Bastille on 14 July 1789 is the symbolic start of the French Revolution.
World War I began in 1914, triggered by the assassination in Sarajevo. | O | The assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand in Sarajevo helped ignite WWI in 1914.
The Industrial Revolution first began in Japan in the late 18th century. | X | The Industrial Revolution began in Britain in the late 18th century, not Japan.
The Declaration of Independence of the United States was adopted in 1776. | O | The U.S. Declaration of Independence was adopted on 4 July 1776.
The Roman Empire was founded in the 20th century. | X | The Roman Empire dates to antiquity (traditionally from 27 BC), not the 20th century.
The Cold War was a period of geopolitical tension mainly between the United States and the Soviet Union. | O | The Cold War was the post-WWII rivalry between the U.S.-led West and the Soviet-led East.
World War II ended in 1945. | O | World War II ended in 1945 after beginning in 1939.
Christopher Columbus reached the Americas in 1492. | O | Columbus crossed the Atlantic and reached the Americas region in 1492.
In which year did World War II end? | 1)1945 2)1918 3)1939 4)1950 | 1 | World War II ended in 1945.
The storming of which fortress-prison symbolized the start of the French Revolution in 1789? | 1)The Bastille 2)The Tower of London 3)The Louvre 4)Versailles | 1 | The storming of the Bastille on 14 July 1789 symbolized the revolution's beginning.
Q: Which wall divided East and West Berlin and fell in 1989? (name it) | A: berlin wall;the berlin wall | The Berlin Wall divided the city from 1961 and fell in 1989, symbolizing the Cold War's end.
Q: Which ancient civilization built the pyramids at Giza? (name the civilization) | A: egypt;ancient egypt;egyptian;the egyptians;egyptians | The ancient Egyptians built the pyramids at Giza as royal tombs.
The Peace of Westphalia in 1648 ended the Thirty Years' War in Europe. | O | The 1648 Peace of Westphalia ended the Thirty Years' War and helped establish the modern idea of sovereign states.
The Aztec Empire was conquered by the Spanish conquistador Francisco Pizarro. | X | Hernán Cortés led the conquest of the Aztec Empire; Francisco Pizarro conquered the Inca Empire in South America.
Which empire was ruled by Emperor Justinian I, famous for codifying Roman law in the 6th century? | 1)The Ottoman Empire 2)The Holy Roman Empire 3)The Byzantine Empire 4)The Carolingian Empire | 3 | Justinian I ruled the Byzantine Empire and ordered the Corpus Juris Civilis, a landmark codification of Roman law.
The Meiji Restoration of 1868 launched Japan's rapid modernization and industrialization. | O | The Meiji Restoration restored imperial rule in 1868 and set Japan on a course of swift Western-style modernization.
Napoleon Bonaparte was finally defeated at the Battle of Austerlitz in 1815. | X | Napoleon's final defeat came at Waterloo in 1815; Austerlitz in 1805 was actually one of his greatest victories.
Q: Which ancient network of trade routes connected China to the Mediterranean and was named after a prized fabric? | A: silk road;the silk road;silk route;the silk route | The Silk Road linked China with Central Asia, the Middle East, and Europe, carrying silk, goods, and ideas for centuries.
The Black Death of the 14th century killed roughly one-third of Europe's population. | O | The Black Death (1347–1351) is estimated to have killed about a third of Europe's people, reshaping its economy and society.
The revolution that brought the Bolsheviks to power in Russia took place in 1905. | X | The Bolsheviks seized power in the October Revolution of 1917; the 1905 revolution failed to topple the tsar.
Which 1919 treaty formally ended World War I between Germany and the Allied Powers? | 1)The Treaty of Tordesillas 2)The Treaty of Versailles 3)The Treaty of Utrecht 4)The Treaty of Ghent | 2 | The Treaty of Versailles, signed in 1919, ended the war with Germany and imposed heavy reparations on it.
The Ottoman Empire was dissolved after World War I, and the Republic of Turkey was proclaimed in 1923. | O | After defeat in WWI the Ottoman Empire collapsed, and Mustafa Kemal Atatürk proclaimed the Republic of Turkey in 1923.
The Hundred Years' War was fought primarily between England and Spain. | X | The Hundred Years' War (1337–1453) was fought between England and France over claims to the French throne.
Q: Which English charter of 1215 limited the power of the king and influenced later constitutional law? (two words) | A: magna carta;the magna carta;magna charta | Magna Carta, sealed by King John in 1215, restricted royal power and became a foundation for constitutional government.
After the First Opium War, China ceded Hong Kong Island to Britain in 1842. | O | The Treaty of Nanking in 1842 ended the First Opium War and ceded Hong Kong Island to Britain.
In 1588, the Spanish Armada defeated the English navy and secured control of the English Channel. | X | England defeated the Spanish Armada in 1588; storms and English tactics devastated the Spanish fleet.
Who became the first emperor of a unified China in 221 BC? | 1)Kublai Khan 2)Sun Yat-sen 3)Wu Zetian 4)Qin Shi Huang | 4 | Qin Shi Huang unified China in 221 BC, founding the Qin dynasty and taking the title of first emperor.
Genghis Khan founded the Mongol Empire in the early 13th century. | O | Genghis Khan united the Mongol tribes around 1206 and built what became history's largest contiguous land empire.
The Renaissance began in France during the 12th century. | X | The Renaissance began in Italy in the 14th century, spreading to the rest of Europe over the following two centuries.
Q: Who served as British prime minister for most of World War II? (surname is enough) | A: churchill;winston churchill;sir winston churchill | Winston Churchill led Britain as prime minister from 1940 to 1945, through most of World War II.
The Congress of Vienna (1814–1815) reorganized Europe after the Napoleonic Wars. | O | At the Congress of Vienna, the great powers redrew Europe's borders and sought a balance of power after Napoleon's defeat.
Martin Luther posted his Ninety-five Theses in 1417, starting the Protestant Reformation. | X | Luther posted the Ninety-five Theses in 1517, not 1417, an act traditionally seen as the start of the Reformation.
Whose expedition completed the first circumnavigation of the globe between 1519 and 1522? | 1)Vasco da Gama 2)Ferdinand Magellan 3)James Cook 4)Amerigo Vespucci | 2 | Ferdinand Magellan's expedition completed the first circumnavigation in 1522, though Magellan himself died en route.
India gained independence from British rule in 1947. | O | British India became independent in August 1947 and was partitioned into India and Pakistan.
The Berlin Conference of 1884–1885 set the rules for European powers dividing up South America. | X | The Berlin Conference regulated the European colonization and partition of Africa, not South America.
Q: Which city, capital of the Byzantine Empire, fell to the Ottomans in 1453 and is now called Istanbul? | A: constantinople;byzantium | Constantinople fell to the Ottomans under Mehmed II in 1453, ending the Byzantine Empire; the city is today's Istanbul.
